[4] Suspected, monitored, quarantined, prevention

10 Apr 2015 Australia (Canberra): Health worker is being treated for Ebola following a stint at a clinic in West Africa
http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3033517/Health-worker-treated-Ebola-following-stint-clinic-West-Africa.html
[An ill health-care worker, recently returned from working at an Ebola treatment unit in Liberia, has been admitted to isolation at a Canberra hospital. She is considered low-risk for contracting Ebola. Test results are anticipated in 72 hours.]

[Her symptoms, fever and stomach upset, are consistent with many possible etiologies. Since she didn't treat any Ebola patients while in Africa, she is considered low risk. See next item. - Mod.LK]

11 Apr 2015 Australia (Canberra): Initial Ebola tests clear Canberra health care worker of virus
http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-04-11/early-tests-clear-canberra-health-care-worker-of-ebola/6385606
[Patient is considered low-risk. Patient remains in isolation as a precaution. 1st of 2 Ebola tests returned negative. 2nd test will be definitive]

11 Apr 2015 Canada: Chief Public Health Officer to visit Ebola treatment centers in West Africa
http://cnews.canoe.ca/CNEWS/Canada/2015/04/11/22338716.html?cid=rssnewscanada

8 Apr 2015 Liberia: Land owners block road to Ebola burial site
http://allafrica.com/stories/201504090797.html?viewall=1
[The only road to the special Ebola burial site was closed. Assistant Chief Elder of Giah Town, Daniel Sackor, stated the total amount for the 25-acre [10.1 ha] land was USD 50 000; the government paid USD 25 000 to them on 2 Dec 2014 and it has not yet paid the balance of USD 25 000]

[The site is being managed by Global Communities, an international non-governmental organization; but the disagreement is with the government. - Mod.LK]

10 Apr 2015 Liberia: Disposing of Ebola waste in Liberia
https://www.youtube.com/watch?feature=player_embedded&v=nFwfoSOe3Yc
[Outbreak containment requires the safe disposal of waste. Each Ebola patient has been estimated by Occupational Health and Safety to generate 465 cubic feet of solid waste weighing over 1000 pounds, roughly 30 to 40 times more than regular hospital patients. Taken together, all of the linens, clothes, scrubs, towels, and other daily needs, as well as liquid waste due to vomiting, diarrhea, bleeding, etc., the cost of Ebola waste disposal totals about USD 1000 per barrel. This volume of waste poses a significant and hazardous challenge. - Mod.LK]

8 Apr 2015 Sierra Leone: Ebola resurfaces at Kroo Bay
http://allafrica.com/stories/201504090982.html
[There has been another confirmed Ebola case reported in Kroo Bay, a sprawling, densely populated slum community on the Atlantic coast, in the Western Area. Residents are concerned about poor sanitary conditions (there are only 6 public toilets for a population of about 10 000, and clean drinking water availability is inadequate). The home of the Ebola-infected patient is under quarantine.]

[Such flare-ups of cases may continue for some time what with such poor sanitary conditions. Investment in improving the standard of living of these communities will go a long way to improving the public health. - Mod LK]

9 Apr 2015 USA (Maryland): American treated for Ebola released from NIH Hospital
http://time.com/3816352/american-ebola-hospital-released/
[The patient was admitted to the National Institutes of Health facility on 13 Mar 2015, and discharged from NIH on Thu 9 Apr 2015 (28-day hospitalization). Patient was discharged after 2 negative tests for Ebola virus. While in Sierra Leone, patient worked as a volunteer for Partners in Health, and was one of several workers exposed to Ebola, but was the only one who contracted the disease. The others brought back to the USA were monitored and discharged. The recently discharged NIH patient is 1 of 2 patients successfully treated for Ebola at NIH; the other patient was the Dallas nurse discharged on 1 Oct 2014.]

10 Apr 2015 USA: CDC to launch Ebola mobile training app for clinicians
http://hitconsultant.net/2015/04/10/cdc-to-launch-ebola-mobile-training-app-for-clinicians/
[US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention will launch an intuitive coaching app for clinicians, providing instructions for donning and doffing of personal protective equipment, quiz to facilitate monitoring of status for priority personnel, and the ability to provide customized content.]

10 Apr 2015: USA (Georgia): Inside Emory's labs
http://www.11alive.com/story/news/local/emory/2015/04/09/emory-ebola-atlanta/25543943/
[Article and video]

12 Apr 2015: USA (Ohio) Test result comes back negative for Ebola
http://www.toledonewsnow.com/story/28783220/test-result-comes-back-negative-for-ebola
[The blood test result came back negative for Ebola. This, after a child patient visiting Toledo from Liberia was sick and had a fever for several days, and was tested for the virus out of an abundance of caution.]

Region
------
9 Apr 2015 West Africa: Ebola lockdowns: Anything to "get to zero"
http://www.irinnews.org/report/101346/ebola-lockdowns-anything-to-get-to-zero
[On 2 occasions in 2014, and one in March 2015, Sierra Leoneans participated in lockdowns as part of the country's efforts to reach 0 Ebola virus infections. While the lockdowns were successful, it is difficult for the public to stay confined at home and go days in a row without wages]

10 Apr 2015 West Africa: 'Fearless' Ebola nurse trains at Emory University
http://us.cnn.com/2015/04/10/health/fatu-kekula-nursing-emory/index.html
[Before Ebola struck Liberia, Fatu Kekula was finishing her nursing degree, but that ended when the school closed. 8 months ago, she saved most of her family from Ebola by using trash bags, rubber boots, and chlorine. Now, thanks to generous donors, she attends Emory University Nell Hodgson Woodruff School of Nursing in the USA. In addition to other studies, Kekula has asked for special training on certain skills, such as caring for burns, a common type of injury because children in Liberia sometimes fall into the open fires used for cooking.]

