http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2015/ihr-ec-ebola/en/
[IHR=International Health Regulations Committee. Emergency Committee met on 9 Apr 2015. The committee concluded the Ebola outbreak constitutes a Public Health Emergency of International Concern, and recommended that all previous temporary recommendations should be extended.]

11 Apr 2015: Ebola survivors face health issues
http://www.digitaljournal.com/life/health/ebola-survivors-face-health-issues/article/430518
[Ebola survivors can face problems with eye (clouded vision, progressive visual loss, blindness) and joint problems, as well as continuing fatigue]

Drugs, vaccines, research
-------------------------
8 Apr 2015: Scoping review -- Ebola, the killer virus
http://www.idpjournal.com/content/4/1/15

9 Apr 2015: Squabbles over testing methods hamper search for Ebola vaccine
http://www.nasdaq.com/article/squabbles-over-testing-methods-hamper-search-for-ebola-vaccine-20150409-00880#ixzz3WqBZqN1Z
[Randomized, placebo-controlled trials are regarded as the best scientific way to evaluate medical products. However, giving a placebo to a person infected with a highly lethal disease raises ethical issues.]

10 Apr 2015: Tekmira gets nod for more Ebola drug testing http://www.marketwatch.com/story/tekmira-gets-nod-for-more-ebola-drug-testing-2015-04-10
[According to the makers of the drug TKM-Ebola, the United States Food and Drug Administration will allow it to administer either the drug or a placebo once daily for a one-week safety trial. Trials will begin again in a few weeks. FDA had placed a clinical hold on the drug in July 2014 until more information on safety and effectiveness could be provided. The FDA hold was modified in August 2014 when it approved the drug's use on those expected to have been infected by the Ebola virus]

10 Apr 2015: Don't think open access is important? It might have prevented much of the Ebola outbreak
https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20150409/17514230608/dont-think-open-access-is-important-it-might-have-prevented-much-ebola-outbreak.shtml
[The "conventional wisdom" among public health authorities was the Ebola outbreak in Liberia, Guinea, and Sierra Leone was -- aside from a Swiss primatologist who contracted Ebola virus from an autopsy of a primate in 1994 -- a "new phenomenon" which had not been seen before 2013. However, a research team reviewing old documents found many studies "buried behind research paywalls," revealing there was significant evidence of antibodies to the Ebola virus in Liberia and in other nearby nations.]

10 Apr 2015 Cell Reports: An Intrinsically Disordered Peptide from Ebola Virus VP35 Controls Viral RNA Synthesis by Modulating Nucleoprotein-RNA Interactions
http://www.cell.com/cell-reports/abstract/S2211-1247%2815%2900303-4

